// p78 — Set operator overloads: union (`s1 + s2`) and difference
// (`s1 - s2`). Also a latent dispatch bug fixed (v3.19.0).
//
// Set has had `.union(other)`, `.intersection(other)`, and
// `.difference(other)` as named methods since v2.x. v3.19.0 adds
// operator-overload aliases as Quirk-side wrappers:
//
//   define __add(self, other: Set) -> Set { return self.union(other) }
//   define __sub(self, other: Set) -> Set { return self.difference(other) }
//
// Sema is taught `Set + Set → Set` and `Set - Set → Set` so the
// arithmetic gate doesn't reject the operator types. The Codegen
// dispatch picks up __add/__sub through the per-struct method
// registry from v3.15.0.
//
// One latent Codegen bug surfaced during this work and got fixed
// alongside: the member-access dispatch had a "triple-underscore
// fallback" (`getFunction(typeName + "___" + memberName)`) that
// was intended to find dunder methods like `__get`/`__init` but
// matched anything if a same-name magic method existed. With
// `__add` introduced, `s1.add(1)` started routing to `Set___add`
// (taking an Int and a Set) — SIGSEGV. The fallback now only
// fires when memberName already starts with `_`, so dunder
// lookups still resolve and bare-name calls hit the right method.

s1 := Set()
s1.add(1); s1.add(2)
s2 := Set()
s2.add(2); s2.add(3)

u: Set := s1 + s2
print(u.size())     // = 3 (union of {1,2,3})

d: Set := s1 - s2
print(d.size())     // = 1 ({1})
print(d.has(1))     // = true
print(d.has(2))     // = false (in s1 AND s2, removed by diff)

// Operands left intact.
print(s1.size())    // = 2
print(s2.size())    // = 2

// Original named methods still work.
print(s1.union(s2).size())       // = 3
print(s1.intersection(s2).size()) // = 1 ({2})
print(s1.difference(s2).size())   // = 1
